{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1783904149,"nonce":"dxOOsmmE+P10TaJMDJu89HXmKqI=","title":"MySQL unique index/constraint column prefix lengths don't round-trip","message":"Split off from 0e296c4 (non-unique prefix indexes, MERGED). MySQL exposes a unique index (`CREATE UNIQUE INDEX ... (col(n))` or `UNIQUE KEY (col(n))`) as a UNIQUE row in information_schema.TABLE_CONSTRAINTS. squealy's `key_constraints` introspection reconstructs it as a neutral unique `Constraint`, which has no per-column prefix-length field, so the prefix is lost and a published unique prefix index re-plans as churn (or, from an external DB, deploys as a full-column unique constraint).\n\n0e296c4's MySQL renderer now REJECTS a unique IndexModel carrying prefix_lengths (safe: no silent churn) as an interim. Full support needs: a prefix-length field on the unique `Constraint` model, reading STATISTICS.SUB_PART in `key_constraints`, and rendering `UNIQUE KEY (col(n))`. Broader than the non-unique secondary-index case 0e296c4 covered (touches the shared Constraint model + all backends that render uniques).","files":null}]}